    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>The wellness industry discovered the gut microbiome and immediately oversold it. By 2020, it was possible to buy probiotic supplements claiming to improve mood, reduce anxiety, enhance focus, and support brain health. The science had barely established that gut bacteria influenced the nervous system at all, and the products were already promising to optimize it. The gap between research reality and commercial claim was spectacular even by supplement industry standards.</p>

      <p>This is unfortunate, because the underlying science — stripped of the marketing — is genuinely interesting and increasingly robust. The gut-brain axis is real. The microbiome's influence on neurological function is real. The mechanisms are being worked out. What isn't real is the confident translation of early-stage findings into specific product recommendations.</p>

      <p>This piece is an attempt to describe what the research actually shows, with appropriate fidelity to both what is established and what is not.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="architecture" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Architecture</h2>

      <p>The gut and the brain are connected by three parallel systems operating simultaneously.</p>

      <p><strong>The vagus nerve</strong> carries signals bidirectionally between the enteric nervous system — the "second brain" embedded in the gut wall — and the central nervous system. The gut contains approximately 500 million neurons and produces 95% of the body's serotonin, 50% of its dopamine precursors, and a range of neurotransmitters and neuropeptides that directly or indirectly influence brain function. Vagal afferents are continuously monitoring gut chemistry and reporting upward.</p>

      <p><strong>The immune system</strong> is the connection most biology courses omit. The gut contains approximately 70% of the body's immune tissue. Gut bacteria continuously interact with this immune layer, producing metabolites that either promote or suppress systemic inflammation. Pro-inflammatory or anti-inflammatory signals generated at the gut-immune interface enter the bloodstream and reach the brain, influencing microglial activation and neuroinflammatory tone. This is the pathway by which gut dysbiosis — an imbalanced microbiome — drives neuroinflammation.</p>

      <p><strong>The circulatory pathway</strong> is the most direct: short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs), tryptophan metabolites, bile acids, and other bacterial metabolites produced in the colon enter the blood and cross the blood-brain barrier directly or modulate neurological function through peripheral receptor signaling.</p>

      <p>These three channels operate in parallel. The result is a system of gut-brain communication that is far more extensive than the "gut feeling" metaphor suggests.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Three Pathways of Gut-Brain Communication</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Vagus nerve:</strong> 500 million gut neurons sending bidirectional signals to the brain</li>
        <li><strong>Immune system:</strong> 70% of immune tissue resides in the gut, driving systemic inflammatory tone</li>
        <li><strong>Circulatory:</strong> SCFAs, tryptophan metabolites, and bile acids crossing the blood-brain barrier</li>
        <li><strong>Serotonin:</strong> 95% of the body's serotonin is produced in the gut</li>
