    </div>

    <section id="evidence" class="reveal">
      <h2>What the Evidence Actually Shows</h2>

      <p><strong>Depression and anxiety.</strong> The association between gut microbiome composition and mental health outcomes is now consistent across dozens of studies. People with major depressive disorder show reliably altered microbiome profiles: reduced diversity overall, lower abundance of specific bacteria including <em>Lactobacillus</em> and <em>Bifidobacterium</em> species, and higher abundance of pro-inflammatory taxa. Similar patterns appear in anxiety disorders.</p>

      <p>What these studies cannot establish is causality from correlation. Does dysbiosis cause depression, or does depression — through stress hormones, altered diet, and sedentary behavior — cause dysbiosis? Almost certainly both. The relationship is bidirectional and self-reinforcing. Stress alters gut motility and bacterial composition; altered composition drives inflammation that amplifies stress reactivity.</p>

      <p>The strongest causal evidence comes from germ-free animal models and fecal microbiota transplant (FMT) studies. Germ-free mice — raised without any gut bacteria — show abnormal stress responses and anxiety-like behavior that can be partially normalized by colonizing them with bacteria from normal mice. FMT studies in rodents have shown that transferring gut contents from depressed humans to germ-free rodents can produce depression-like behavior in the recipients. These findings are striking, though the translation from rodent to human is always uncertain.</p>

      <p>Human FMT studies for psychiatric indications are in early stages. Case reports and small open-label trials have suggested mood improvements in patients receiving FMT for other indications, but no large randomized controlled trial has established FMT as a psychiatric treatment.</p>

      <p><strong>Neurodegenerative disease.</strong> The microbiome-Parkinson's connection is the most developed in the neurodegeneration space. A specific pattern — the "Parkinson's microbiome" — has been identified in multiple independent cohorts: increased <em>Akkermansia</em> and <em>Desulfovibrio</em> species, decreased SCFA-producing bacteria. More remarkably, post-mortem studies have found alpha-synuclein aggregates (the pathological protein of Parkinson's) in the enteric nervous system of patients, sometimes years before brain pathology is detectable. The working hypothesis is that Parkinson's disease may, in some cases, originate in the gut and travel to the brain via the vagus nerve. This is not confirmed, but it is taken seriously enough that gut biopsy as an early Parkinson's detection method is being actively investigated.</p>

      <p>For Alzheimer's, the microbiome story runs primarily through inflammation and the blood-brain barrier. Dysbiosis drives systemic inflammation, which degrades barrier integrity, which allows inflammatory mediators into brain tissue, which activates microglia and drives neuroinflammation. Several bacterial species produce amyloid-like proteins that may seed human amyloid aggregation, though this remains experimental.</p>

      <p><strong>Cognition.</strong> Human evidence for microbiome influence on cognitive performance is largely associational: higher microbiome diversity and SCFA-producing bacteria correlate with better cognitive metrics in observational studies. The directionality remains to be established.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
